{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506474"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2538"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2538"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.05,0.1,0.29,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident in which he was knocked off his motor scooter. He is able to provide a clear history and complains of left sided lower chest pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is breathing normally. His pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 110/70mmHg, temperature 37\u00b0C, respiratory rate 18/min and SaO2 98% on room air. Examination of his chest is normal, apart from restriction of movement on deep inspiration. There is tenderness and guarding in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from pain relief, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for observation","Chest drain","CT angiogram","Catheter embolisation","Trauma laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer for this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecatheter embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient has been involved in a road traffic accident and has sustained an injury to his spleen, one of the most common solid organs to be damaged in blunt trauma. The CT scan demonstrates a grade III splenic injury. Higher grades describe a more severe injury (haematoma and/or laceration), with grades I and II considered low grade and grades IV and V high grade (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of splenic injury ranges from non-operative approaches (e.g. continued observation and/or repeat imaging), to minimally invasive strategies (i.e. catheter embolisation), and finally to surgical management options (e.g. partial and total splenectomy). Surgical management options are indicated in the setting of haemodynamic instability from haemorrhage and peritonitis. Generally speaking, salvaging the spleen is preferable, mainly due to the important role the organ plays in the immune system. Patients who undergo splenectomy are at increased risk of severe infection, even decades later.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the CT scan shows an injury that is likely amenable to embolisation, making this option the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs there is a reasonably significant injury present, some sort of intervention is required. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmitting the patient for observation\u003C/strong\u003E as a stand-alone management strategy is not sufficient. Following embolisation, patients should be closely monitored, as any evidence of treatment failure (i.e. ongoing bleeding) will warrant operative intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence to suggest the presence of a pneumothorax and/or haemothorax, making \u003Cstrong\u003Echest drain\u003C/strong\u003E insertion an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E might provide more detail around the nature of the injury and further localise the bleed, evidence suggests that CT angiography in addition to a standard contrast-enhanced CT is unnecessary in most patients. As such, CT angiography is not the best answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient does not seem to have sustained any other intra-abdominal trauma, a \u003Cstrong\u003Etrauma laparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not required at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with Grade III or IV splenic injuries should be considered for angioembolisation."],"references":["Zarzaur BL, Rozycki GS. An update on nonoperative management of the spleen in adults. Trauma Surgery \u0026 Acute Care Open. 2017;2(1). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5877897/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2538"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14419"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20591"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14419"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/03289e7d-9b8c-4f2c-a077-709b6368e866.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/stora